## Thread.Abort → Cooperative Cancellation (.NET 8)

Your code is a **timeout enforcement** pattern. In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` and `Thread.ResetAbort()` is obsolete (`SYSLIB0006`).

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException on timeout
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }

    // Preferred: async overload
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout, CancellationToken externalToken = default)
    {
        using var cts = CancellationTokenSource
            .CreateLinkedTokenSource(externalToken);
        cts.CancelAfter(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await Task.Run(work, cts.Token)
                             .WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (externalToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw; // external cancellation — propagate as-is
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Key Changes

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `new Thread(...)` + `thread.Abort()` | `Task.Run` + `CancellationTokenSource` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Removed — not needed |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` | `Task.WaitAsync(token)` |

### Critical Pitfalls

1. **Cancellation is cooperative, not preemptive.** If `work()` is a long-running CPU loop that never checks the token, `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` won't interrupt it — the task keeps running in the background. To fix this, refactor `work` to accept a `CancellationToken`:

   ```csharp
   public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
   {
       using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
       return Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token)
                  .WaitAsync(cts.Token)
                  .GetAwaiter().GetResult();
   }

   // Callers must check the token:
   executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(ct =>
   {
       foreach (var item in items)
       {
           ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
           Process(item);
       }
       return result;
   }, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
   ```

2. **Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`.** It's `IDisposable` — leaking it causes timer leaks. Always use `using`.

3. **Blocking I/O won't be interrupted** by token cancellation. Replace `Thread.Sleep(ms)` with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)`, and use async I/O overloads that accept `CancellationToken`.

4. **Truly uncooperative code** (third-party libs, native calls) cannot be cancelled with tokens. The only reliable option is to move the work to a **child process** and call `Process.Kill()` on timeout.
